ralist of the United States North Pacific Exploring Expedition, where he collected and classified hundreds of marine animals. Upon his return, he joined renowned naturalist Spencer F. Baird at the Smithsonian Institution to create its department of invertebrate zoology. He also founded and led the irreverent and fun-loving Megatherium Club, which included many notable naturalists. In 1865, Stimpson focused on turning the Chicago Academy of Sciences into one of the largest and most important museums in the country. Tragically, the museum was destroyed in the Great Chicago Fire of 1871, and Stimpson died of tuberculosis soon after, before he could restore his scientific legacy. This first-ever biography of William Stimpson situates his work in the context of his time. As one of few to collaborate with both Agassiz and Baird, Stimpson's life provides insight into the men who shaped a generation of naturalists—the last before intense specialization caused naturalists to give way to biologists. Historians of science and general readers interested in biographies, science, and history will enjoy this compelling biography.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aNatural historyzUnited States. 0aNaturalistszUnited StatesvBiography. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aGeneral Science. 4aNature Guides & Natural History. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Environmentalists & Naturalists.2bisacsh  aearly naturalists, Specer F. Baird, Smithsonian Institution, invetebrate zoology, Great Chicago Fire, classification of marine animals, United States North Pacific Exploring Expedition, Megatherium Club.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150175812640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501758126423Coveruhttps://www.degruyt